# KSV0125: Restrict container images to trusted registries
# Trivy does not recognize ghcr.io as trusted by default. We use ghcr.io for application images.
# Registry validation is enforced at deployment time via policy/OPA Gatekeeper.
KSV0125

# KSV020, KSV021: runAsUser/runAsGroup > 10000
# OpenShift restricted-v2 SCC assigns namespace-specific UID range (e.g. 1002750000-1002759999).
# Cannot hardcode in template; OpenShift injects at deploy time.
KSV020
KSV021

# KSV030, KSV104: seccompProfile
# OpenShift restricted SCC forbids seccomp: "seccomp may not be set".
KSV030
KSV104

# CVE-2026-3260: Undertow Denial of Service via premature multipart/form-data
# parsing on GET requests.
#
# Severity: MEDIUM. Backend (Spring Boot) intentionally uses Undertow instead
# of Tomcat (see backend/pom.xml — tomcat-starter excluded, undertow-starter
# added).
#
# Why we're accepting this temporarily:
#   - The only fixed Undertow release at the time of writing is 2.4.0.Beta1,
#     a development build. We don't want a `.Beta` server on production.
#   - The attack vector (large multipart body in a GET) is blocked upstream:
#       * Caddy/Coraza in front of the backend caps request body size.
#       * OpenShift Route default request body cap (1 MiB) applies.
#       * The whole /api surface is gated by Cognito JWT validation, so
#         only authenticated IDIR users can reach the upstream at all.
#   - Memory pressure from a single oversized request is bounded by the
#     pod's `memory` limit (800Mi); an attacker can at worst force a pod
#     restart, not exhaust the node.
#
# Re-evaluate when a stable Undertow 2.4.0.Final ships, or when Spring Boot
# 3.5.x's managed Undertow version is bumped to a non-vulnerable release.
# Last reviewed: 2026-05-19.
CVE-2026-3260
